{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17499581","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17499581"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T10:01:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T10:01:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1518"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1518"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.59,0.11,0.03,0.25,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41878"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1518","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1518"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1518"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26850"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"19"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"639"},{"type":"tags","id":"1151"},{"type":"tags","id":"1256"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3473"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3518"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41878","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/41878"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old man is referred to a gastroenterologist for an endoscopy. He has a medical history of long-standing gastro-oesophageal reflux disease (GORD) and well-controlled hypertension. His medications list includes omeprazole, which he has taken for over 15 years, amlodipine and hydrochlorothiazide. The endoscopy has been arranged as surveillance for the development of Barrett\u0027s oesophagus given his age and GORD history in accordance with Cancer Council guidelines. He has no known family history of gastrointestinal disorders. He is a non-smoker and drinks alcohol rarely. On endoscopy, the stomach appears as shown (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Hyperplastic polyps","Peutz-Jeghers syndrome","Gastric varices","Familial adenomatous polyposis","Gastrointestinal Stromal Tumour"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe stomach is carpeted with polyps and these are very likely to be benign, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehyperplastic polyps\u003C/strong\u003E. Achlorhydria (lack of hydrochloric acid) is a well-documented cause of hyperplastic polyp formation and long-term use of a proton pump inhibitor will induce a state of relative achlorhydria.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPeutz-Jeghers syndrome\u003C/strong\u003E (PJS) is a rare autosomal dominant condition. Most patients become symptomatic during the first few decades of life, with the most common feature being mucocutaneous pigmented macules and the second being small bowel hamartomous polyps, but can also affect the stomach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastric varices\u003C/strong\u003E are dilated veins which appear tortuous on endoscopy and would be expected in a patient with known liver cirrhosis. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFamilial adenomatous polyposis\u003C/strong\u003E (FAP) typically causes in excess of 100 polyps along the large intestine and rectum, progressing to colorectal cancer in middle age adults. Polyps can occur in the duodenum and even the stomach but are much less likely. Additionally, this man has no family history of FAP.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGastrointestinal stromal tumours\u003C/strong\u003E (GIST) do tend to affect the stomach in adults at this age. On endoscopy they appear as large submucosal masses and may have ulceration, rather than the picture of numerous polyps shown here.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Long-term use of proton-pump inhibitors can cause hyperplastic stomach polyp formation."],"references":["Kim GH. Proton Pump Inhibitor-Related Gastric Mucosal Changes. Gut Liver. 2020;15(5):646-652. Available at: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC8444106/#:~:text=In%20long%2Dterm%20PPI%20users,can%20be%20observed%20on%20endoscopy."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26850"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1518"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"10432"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"10432","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/10432"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a981da9b-11b3-452b-8153-f6a43408abff.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/a981da9b-11b3-452b-8153-f6a43408abff.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":538,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"26850","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/26850"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-01-25T21:20:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-01-25T21:20:34+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1518"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"41878"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"19","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/19"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2a","name":"General Surgery","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:47:20+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"2"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"re